  |text= '''[[Debbie_Allen|Debbie Allen]]''' (born January 16, 1950 in [[Houston|Houston]], [[Texas|Texas]]) is an American actress, choreographer, director, and producer. She first began receiving critical attention in 1980, when she appeared in the role of Anita in the Broadway revival of [[West_Side_Story|West Side Story]] which earned her a Drama Desk Award. 

She is probably best known for her role as Lydia Grant in the hit 1982 TV series [[Fame_(1982_TV_series)|Fame]]. During the opening montage of each episode, Ms. Grant told her students: "You've got big dreams? You want fame? Well, fame costs. And right here is where you start paying... in sweat." Allen was also lead choreographer for the film and television series, winning two [[Emmy_Award|Emmy Award]]s and one [[Golden_Globe_Award|Golden Globe Award]].

She has a B.A. in classical Greek literature, speech, and theater from [[Howard_University|Howard University]]. She also holds honoris causa Doctors from Howard and the [[University_of_North_Carolina_School_of_the_Arts|North Carolina School for the Arts]]. 
